-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Skye Bank, Naiade Hotels, Aluworks, Law Union
-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 2010-12-13T16:57:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-10/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-cfc-stanbic-unity-bank-of-nigeria.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  declined
for a third trading day, falling 0.1 percent to 1,917.24 by the
1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis. The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  declined 0.6 percent to 7,196.01 by the 1 p.m. close
in Accra.  The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  declined 0.6
percent to 24,287.5, by the close at 2.30 p.m. in Lagos, the
commercial capital, according to exchange’s website.  Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  shed 0.1 percent to
835.98 at the 5 p.m. close in Windhoek. Kenya’s  All-Share Index 
was closed for a holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Skye Bank Plc  (SKYBANK NL), a Nigerian lender, rose for the
first day in five after it said it would sell its non-banking
units in insurance, mortgage, stock brokerage and trusteeship in
line with a central bank directive. The stock gained 8 kobo, or
1 percent, to 8 naira by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, the
commercial capital.  Law Union and Rock Insurance of Nigeria Plc  (LAWUNION NL)
rose the most in a month after Skye Bank Plc said it will sell
its stake in the insurer. The stock gained 2 kobo, or 4 percent,
to close at 52 kobo by 2:30 p.m. in Lagos.  Aluworks Ghana Ltd.  (ALW GN), a maker of aluminum products,
fell the most in four trading days as investors speculated the
company may post a loss this year. The stock shed 1 pesewa, or
5.9 percent, to 16 pesewas by the 1 p.m. close in Accra, the
capital.  Naiade Resorts Ltd.  (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
slid to its lowest in 2 1/2 months on worries the company’s loss
may deepen. The stock declined 1 rupee, or 4.2 percent, to 23
rupees, the lowest since Sept. 27, by the 1:30 p.m. close in
Port Louis, the capital.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Vincent Nwanma  in Lagos at 
 vnwanma@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
